ealized physical spaces, reclaiming the altered landscape to counteract the violence and loss of the period and creating in the process what Mackenzie, following David Harvey, terms 'spaces of hope.' This unique alliance of French Renaissance studies with cultural geography and eco-criticism demonstrates that sixteenth-century poetry created a powerful sense of place which continues to inform national and regional sentiment today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFrench poetryy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLandscapes in literature. 0aNational characteristics, French, in literature. 0aPastoral poetry, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269381440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442693814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442693814.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK